item.description:
Don't let your database be the bottleneck for frequently accessed data. If your Spring Boot API constantly fetches "hot" information like product catalogs or popular articles from PostgreSQL, you're needlessly burning resources. Caching is your immediate win here.

Spring's `@Cacheable` annotation provides a powerful, declarative way to cache method results. Pair it with Redis as your distributed cache store and watch your API performance soar.

```java
@Service
public class ProductService {

    private final ProductRepository productRepository;

    public ProductService(ProductRepository productRepository) {
        this.productRepository = productRepository;
    }

    @Cacheable(value = "products", key = "#categoryId")
    public List<Product> getProductsByCategory(Long categoryId) {
        // This line only executes if cache misses
        System.out.println("Fetching products from DB for category: " + categoryId);
        return productRepository.findByCategoryId(categoryId);
    }
}
```

With a properly configured `RedisCacheManager` in Spring, this simple annotation ensures `getProductsByCategory` executes its logic only once per `categoryId` until the cache expires. Subsequent calls retrieve data directly from Redis, drastically cutting database load and shaving milliseconds off your response times. Efficient and effective.
